NFL PLAY PREDICTOR¶

A statistical model designed to predict whether a given down will be a designed run, pass, punt, or field goal based on all games played during the 2009 - 2018 NFL seasons¶

Using dataset "NFL Play by Play 2009-2018 (v5).csv" from https://www.kaggle.com/maxhorowitz/nflplaybyplay2009to2016?select=NFL+Play+by+Play+2009-2018+%28v5%29.csv¶

Given that the data set has 255 data points on every play run between 2009 - 2018 and is 667 MB, I decided to trim it down in excel to the the twenty variables I thought might be the most relevant, to be experimented on before I decide on my final feature variables. I chose this data set because it has the most data points to choose from on every play run in the last decade in the NFL. My hypothesis is that it won't be possible to predict plays above roughly 75%-80% of the time, because offenses in the NFL intentionally mix it up. I believe it will be easier to predict field goals and punts than runs vs passes.¶

In [6]:
# Make useful datapoints for game situation
df['last_play_of_half'] = df['half_seconds_remaining'] < 10
df['two_minute_drill'] = df['half_seconds_remaining'] < 180
df['fourth_quarter'] = ((df['game_half'] == 'Half2') & (df['half_seconds_remaining'] < 900))
df['offense_winning'] = df['score_differential'] > 0 
df['two_score_game'] = np.absolute(df['score_differential']) > 8
df['within_three'] = np.absolute(df['score_differential']) < 4
df['field_goal_range'] = df['yardline_100'] < 45

A few things can be interpreted from this graph. Teams are more likely to attempt a field goal as they get closer to the endzone on fourth down. Teams are more likely to run when the yards to go is shorter on fourth down and more likely to pass when yards to go is higher. Teams are more and more likely to punt as they get farther from a first down and farther from the end zone on fourth down.¶

Insights¶

Due to coaches intentionally adding randomness to their play type selection in order to keep the defense on its toes, I began this project knowing it wouldn't be possible to predict play type perfectly. My first thought was to use the KNN algorithm in order to predict the next play call. This method wasn't a total failure, but was a little disapointing, as even after experimenting with many different combinations of feature variables, and number of neighbors, I couldn't get the accuracy above 70%, which isn't great considering predicting punts and field goals should be fairly easy. Just by watching a game, an average fan should be able to predict run and pass plays roughly as well as the KNN algorithm performed. I believe that this is because football is so situational, and in different times of the game, different variables carry more or less weight. For example, being within field goal range doesn't matter if you're down by more than three with less than a few minutes left. This is why a decision tree felt like a better fit. It performed better than the KNN algorithm across the board. I was especially impressed by the model's near perfect f1-score on predicting punts and field goals, as coaches have the option to punt, go for it, or kick a field goal on fourth. I believe the situational nature of the game, and the situational feature variables I added to the data set are the reason the decision tree performed better than I expected.¶
